[1
Date: Fri, 5 Jun 1998 10:47:19 -0500 (EST)
From: Gerald L. McLaughlin, Ph.D <gmclaugh@iupui.edu>

Re: PRO> Coxsackie B4 & diabetes (02), Hal Nash said:
> >Regardless, the discovery is significant and lends support to an old
> >hypothesis that all disease, including organic disease, is the result of a
> >microbe. The recent ProMED-mail discussion regarding _Chlamydia
> >pneumoniae_ and its possible link to atherosclerosis is but another
example.
and Dr M. J. Wysocki <wysocki@who.ernet.in> added:
> >It is probably a little risky to say that "diabetes..... is caused by a
virus...

Testable hypotheses are inherently risky; one discards or modifies until
the remaining hypotheses become theories. I think Koch would be aghast at
the way that "Koch's postulates" are held as the necessary standard for
proving roles for infections in chronic diseases. Even "modified Koch's
postulates", based on correlations and other criteria, fail to account for
the likely interplay of host genotype and environment, infections,
immunity, and chronic diseases.
Rous was at least partly right about cancer and infections, and perhaps
largely right; infections generate liver and cervical cancers, and
minimally drive mutations in specific genes (often signal pathway genes)
that lead to cancer. Mouse models of multiple sclerosis indicate that the
condition arises certainly in some genetic backgrounds, only given
infection or immunization in others, and never in other genetic
backgrounds.
Asthma, premature aging of the immune system, and other phenomena are other
diseases influenced by antigen exposure including histories of infection.
--
Gerald L. McLaughlin, Ph.D.
