[2
Date: Fri, 05 Jun 1998 00:04:04 -0400
From: Andrew J. McLeod <mcleodaj@umdnj.edu>

Hal Nash <hnash@wyoming.com> wrote:
> This sounds more like a case of cross-reactivity than autoimmunity. Or am
> I splitting hairs here? The normal immune response to one of the 11
> proteins of the Coxsackie B4 virus just happens to cross-react with a
> protein found in pancreatic islets. This seems to me to be more accurately
> described as accidental. It is my understanding that autoimmunity results
> from the "escape" of sequestered clones which recognize human antigens.
I am sorry to "split hairs" in return, but the "sequestered clone theory"
is only one of several theories concerning the origins of autoimmunity.
Additionally, regardless of the initiating event (some theory does still
attribute the possibility of cross-reactivity or prokaryotic infection -
whether it be bacterial, viral or otherwise - such theories are currently
being investigated in the case of SLE or Lupus) an autoimmune process, once
triggered, becomes a self-escalating event (again theorized to be due to
many possible mechanisms, such as the formation of anti-idiotype antibody
cascades, etc.)
One example of a theory that wraps much of this together under one title is
the "altered antigen" theory, where due to chemical or physical means, a
"self-antigen" is modified or altered and instead recognized as foreign.
Such mechanisms may be physical or chemical injury to tissue, tissue
necrosis, or even temperature (such play roles in Paroxysmal Cold
Hemoglobinuria and Raynauld's Disease).
It is also possible that whether the antigen STARTS OUT as "self" or
"foreign", cross-reactive epitopes cause a cascade of now-auto-immune
responses. Hapten-carrier complexes generate completely NEW antigenic
epitopes, which may cause the body great distress.
Please forgive me if I in any way have exuded any tone of
"know-it-all"-ness, and any of my colleagues in this field please correct
me if I have misstated fact in any way. However this has simply been my
personal area of interest and involvement both in the clinical laboratory
as well as research for some time. My comments are meant strictly as
discussion and in no way in offense.
--
Andrew J. McLeod, MLT (ASCP,) EMT-B/D
Medical Laboratory Technician (ASCP Certified)
Dept. of Clinical Laboratory Sciences - Medical Technology Progam
University of Medicine and Dentistry of N.J.
Newark, New Jersey, U.S.A.
